"""
MKT Context Commentary — Revelation chapters 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-revelation-1-5.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/revelation.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/revelation.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- Historical context of all seven cities drawn from Roman-era sources:
  Ephesus, Smyrna, Pergamum, Thyatira, Sardis, Philadelphia, Laodicea
- Merkabah mysticism context for the throne-room (chs 4–5)
- Imperial cult as the primary social pressure on the seven churches
- Trade guilds and the idol-food dilemma (not merely personal piety but economic survival)
- Patmos exile identified as Roman relegatio in insulam under Domitian (81–96 CE)
- "Lord's Day" noted as first occurrence of this term in early Christian literature
- 24 elders: both 24 priestly courses (1 Chr 24) and 12+12 readings acknowledged
- The sealed scroll treated as an opisthographon (scroll written on both sides)
  within the framework of Roman testamentary sealing practice
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

REVELATION = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>The book opens as an <em>apokalypsis</em> — the disclosure of what has been hidden. By the late first century CE, apocalyptic literature was a well-established Jewish genre: Daniel, 1 Enoch, 4 Ezra, 2 Baruch, the Apocalypse of Abraham, and the Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs all belong to this tradition. The genre conventions were familiar to Jewish-Christian readers: a seer receives heavenly visions, heavenly figures interpret them, and cosmic events are disclosed that illuminate the meaning of earthly suffering and history. John\'s Revelation is simultaneously the most Jewish of NT books (it is saturated with OT imagery) and the most subversive toward Rome (it codes its Roman critique in apocalyptic imagery).</p>',
    "2": '<p>John identifies himself as a witness to \'the word of God and the testimony of Jesus Christ.\' The language of testimony and witness (<em>martyria</em>) had particular weight in communities experiencing persecution — the one who testifies before authorities is the <em>martys</em>, whose testimony might cost his life. The apostolic witness-chain (from eyewitnesses of Jesus through authorized teachers) was the ground of Christian authority in the late first century, before the NT canon was formally established. John\'s authority rests on his witness-role.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The blessing formula (\'blessed is the one who reads aloud, and blessed are those who hear\') reflects the practice of public reading in early Christian assemblies. Paul\'s letters were read aloud in gathered congregations (1 Thess 5:27; Col 4:16), and Jewish synagogue practice of the Torah reading was adapted into the church\'s Sunday assembly. A single <em>anagnōstēs</em> (reader) would read while the community listened — most members of the congregation were not literate, and personal copies of texts were extremely rare. Revelation was composed to be performed, not privately read.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The seven churches of Asia are identifiable cities on a roughly circular mail route beginning at Ephesus: Ephesus → Smyrna → Pergamum → Thyatira → Sardis → Philadelphia → Laodicea → and back toward Ephesus. This route corresponds to the Roman provincial postal system (the <em>cursus publicus</em>), making the Revelation a practical circular letter carried by a messenger. The selection of seven (not all the churches in Asia — Colossae, Hierapolis, Troas, and others existed) is symbolic: seven = completeness. What is addressed to seven is for all.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The threefold title of Christ — faithful witness, firstborn from the dead, ruler of the kings of the earth — is a deliberate counter-claim to Roman imperial titles. The emperor Domitian (81–96 CE) was addressed as <em>Dominus et Deus noster</em> (our Lord and God) and claimed divine sonship. To call Jesus \'ruler of the kings of the earth\' — including, implicitly, the emperor — was a politically charged assertion. The \'firstborn from the dead\' title invokes the Jewish resurrection hope: the resurrection of the dead as the vindication of the righteous at the end of history.</p>',
    "6": '<p>\'A kingdom of priests\' directly quotes Exod 19:6 (LXX: <em>basileion hierateuma</em>), Israel\'s covenant identity at Sinai. The application to the Christian community does not abolish Israel\'s calling but transfers and fulfills it in the new covenant people. In the Roman imperial system, priests were mediators between the divine and human realms — a social function of enormous prestige. To call every believer a priest upended the priestly-hierarchical structure of both Roman religion and the Jerusalem temple system.</p>',
    "7": '<p>\'Behold, he is coming with the clouds\' draws on Dan 7:13, where \'one like a son of man\' comes with the clouds of heaven to receive universal dominion. This was a widely-known text in Second Temple Judaism — the Parables of Enoch (1 Enoch 37–71) develop the Son of Man figure extensively, and the Dead Sea Scrolls community awaited a similar figure. \'Those who pierced him\' and \'all the tribes of the earth will mourn\' applies Zech 12:10-12 to the returning Christ — in Zechariah, Israel mourns for the one they pierced; in Revelation, the mourning is universal. The combining of Dan 7 and Zech 12 was an established early Christian interpretation.</p>',
    "8": '<p>\'The Lord God Almighty\' (<em>Kyrios ho Theos ho Pantokrator</em>) is the LXX rendering of <em>YHWH Tsvaot</em> (LORD of Hosts). The claim that God is \'Alpha and Omega\' — comprehensive, from first to last — directly counters the Roman imperial ideology in which the emperor was the axis of history. Domitian\'s insistence on being addressed as <em>Dominus et Deus noster</em> (Our Lord and God) made the Christian confession of Jesus as Lord an act of political as well as religious resistance.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Patmos is a small volcanic island in the Aegean (about 13 square miles), part of the Dodecanese chain, roughly 37 miles southwest of Miletus and 60 miles from Ephesus. The Roman practice of <em>relegatio in insulam</em> (banishment to an island) was a penalty for political offenders of social standing — those who merited death were executed; those of standing who posed political risk were exiled. The exile was accompanied by confiscation of property. That John was exiled rather than executed suggests he had some social status and that the authorities considered his influence worth containing rather than creating a martyr.</p>',
    "10": '<p>\'The Lord\'s Day\' (<em>hē kyriakē hēmera</em>) is the earliest occurrence of this specific phrase in surviving Christian literature (Didache 14:1, probably slightly later, also uses it). By the late first century, Sunday had become the regular day of Christian assembly in commemoration of the resurrection (Acts 20:7; 1 Cor 16:2; Justin Martyr, <em>First Apology</em> 67). The choice of \'Lord\'s Day\' may be a deliberate counter to the imperial <em>dies Augusti</em> (days honoring the emperor) observed in Roman religious calendars. The trumpet-sound that initiates the vision echoes the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16) and the call to prophetic proclamation (Isa 58:1).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The command to write to the seven specific churches signals that Revelation was designed as a circular letter following the Roman postal route through the cities of the province of Asia (modern western Turkey). The order — Ephesus, Smyrna, Pergamum, Thyatira, Sardis, Philadelphia, Laodicea — is the order of the road from Ephesus northward, then inland, then south. A single messenger could carry the letter along this route, ensuring each community received it in sequence. The letters to the seven churches (chs 2–3) are thus not abstract categories but pastoral communications to real congregations in identifiable cities, each with its specific social pressures.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The seven golden lampstands immediately evoke the seven-branched menorah of the tabernacle (Exod 25:31-40; 37:17-24), the one light source in Israel\'s holy place, which the priests were responsible to tend and keep burning (Exod 27:20-21; Lev 24:2-4). In the second temple period, the menorah was the symbol of Israel\'s light-bearing vocation among the nations (cf. Zech 4:2-6). The redeployment of the menorah as seven separate lampstands (not a single seven-branched stand) represents seven churches as the new menorah — plural, distributed, worldwide.</p>',
    "13": '<p>\'One like a son of man\' is drawn from Dan 7:13-14, where the figure who receives universal dominion before the Ancient of Days is described in these terms. In the Second Temple period, the \'son of man\' figure had been developed in considerable detail — the Parables of Enoch (1 Enoch 37–71), the Son of Man sayings in the Gospels, and the Danielic exegesis in 4 Ezra all show an expectation of a human-divine figure. The \'long robe\' and \'golden sash\' describe the vestments of the high priest (Exod 28:4; Lev 16:4) — the glorified Christ appears in priestly as well as prophetic and royal garments.</p>',
    "14": '<p>\'His head and his hair were white like white wool, like snow\' draws on Dan 7:9 (the Ancient of Days, whose clothing was white as snow and whose hair was like pure wool). This description is applied to God himself in Daniel; its application to Christ in Revelation is one of several places where Revelation attributes to Christ the characteristics of YHWH. \'Eyes like a blazing flame\' comes from Dan 10:6, where the heavenly man whose eyes were like torches of fire appeared to Daniel — the same figure that left Daniel prostrate (Dan 10:8-9), as John also falls (v. 17).</p>',
    "15": '<p>\'Burnished bronze\' (<em>chalkolibanos</em>) recalls the description in Dan 10:6 and Ezek 1:7 (the creatures of the throne-chariot with gleaming bronze). \'Voice like many waters\' is drawn from Ezek 43:2, where the sound of God\'s glory returning to the restored temple is \'like the noise of many waters\' — and Ezek 1:24, where the wings of the living creatures sounded \'like the roar of many waters, like the voice of the Almighty.\' The glorified Christ speaks with the voice of the returning divine glory.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Seven stars in his right hand evoke both the seven planetary deities of Greco-Roman astrology (which controlled human destiny in popular belief) and the seven angels representing the churches. The double-edged sword from his mouth draws on the Roman <em>ius gladii</em> (right of the sword) — the proconsul of Asia, resident in Pergamum, wielded this sword-authority over life and death. Christ\'s counter-claim: the ultimate judicial weapon is not the proconsul\'s sword but the word of Christ. The sword proceeds from his mouth — it is the word of judgment, not a physical weapon.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The prostration response — falling \'as a dead man\' (<em>hōsei nekros</em>) — is the standard OT response to an overwhelming divine encounter: Daniel fell and was \'in a deep sleep, face to the ground\' at the heavenly apparition (Dan 8:17-18; 10:8-12); Ezekiel \'fell on his face\' (Ezek 1:28); Isaiah cried \'Woe is me, I am ruined\' (Isa 6:5). The right hand placed on John to reassure him mirrors Daniel\'s experiences (Dan 8:18; 10:10, 18). The pattern of divine theophany → human prostration → divine reassurance was a recognized form in prophetic commissioning literature.</p>',
    "18": '<p>\'I hold the keys of Death and Hades\' — in Jewish cosmology, the realm of the dead (Sheol/Hades) was locked: Hades was frequently portrayed as a prison from which there was no exit. The key to a city or realm was the symbol of sovereignty over it (Isa 22:22: Eliakim receives the key of the house of David). For the crucified and risen Christ to hold the keys of Death and Hades meant that the ultimate power in the cosmos — the universal human fear of death — was under his authority. This was particularly significant for communities facing Roman execution.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The tripartite formula \'what you have seen, what is now, and what will take place after this\' has generated extensive discussion about Revelation\'s structure: does it map to ch. 1 (the vision), chs. 2-3 (the present state of the churches), and chs. 4-22 (future events)? Or is it a more flexible framework? In any case, the formula reflects the standard apocalyptic disclosure structure — heavenly vision reveals past, present, and future from a God\'s-eye perspective. The prophet is authorized to speak about all three tenses of divine action.</p>',
    "20": '<p>\'The mystery\' (<em>mystērion</em>) is a term with specific weight in both Greek religious context (the mystery religions of Eleusis, Mithras, Isis required secret initiation) and Jewish apocalyptic (Daniel\'s repeated use of <em>rāz</em> = mystery for the hidden plans of God disclosed to the prophet). In Revelation, the mystery is explicitly interpreted: the stars are the angels/messengers of the seven churches; the lampstands are the churches themselves. The revelation democratizes apocalyptic disclosure — the mystery is not a secret for initiates but an open letter to all seven communities.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p>Ephesus was the largest and most important city in the Roman province of Asia, with a population of perhaps 200,000–250,000. It was the main port of entry for the province and the seat of the Roman proconsul when he was visiting the region. The city\'s most famous landmark was the temple of Artemis (the Artemision), one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, which generated enormous income from pilgrimage tourism, religious banking, and the sale of silver shrines (Acts 19:24). Paul had his longest urban ministry there (three years, Acts 18:18-20:1), and Timothy subsequently led the Ephesian community. The letter addresses a church with a significant history and strong doctrinal vigilance.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The Ephesian church\'s \'hard work\' and \'patient endurance\' and inability to tolerate \'wicked people\' reflects the social pressure on an urban Christian community. Trade guilds (<em>collegia</em>) were the social backbone of ancient city life — professional associations for merchants, craftsmen, and artisans that combined economic mutual aid with regular banquets honoring the guild\'s patron deity. Refusing to participate in guild activities (because they involved idol-food and prayers to pagan gods) meant economic marginalization. The Ephesian church\'s vigilance was achieved at real cost.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The \'endurance\' praised in v. 3 is not passive waiting but active perseverance under sustained pressure. In a city dominated by the Artemis cult, where the temple served as a bank, a civic center, and the economic driver of the regional economy, maintaining a distinct Christian identity required ongoing effort. The community had tested would-be apostles (v. 2) — false teachers who presented apostolic credentials were circulating among the churches (cf. 2 Cor 11:13-15; Didache 11-12), and the Ephesian church\'s discernment protected the community from them.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The \'first love\' abandoned at Ephesus is described as a falling from a height (<em>peptōkas</em>). The metaphor of falling from a prior state is common in both Jewish and Greek moral discourse. The loss of initial fervor in established communities was a recognized problem in early Christianity — Paul\'s letters to the Corinthians, Galatians, and Philippians all address it. The irony is that doctrinal vigilance (vv. 2-3) had been maintained while relational vitality was lost — a pattern that often accompanies institutional maturity.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The threat to \'remove your lampstand\' (v. 5) would have been understood in its full civic dimension: a city that lost its Christian community lost its light-bearing witness. In the Roman world, the status of a city depended on its institutions — Ephesus\'s status as <em>neokoros</em> (temple-keeper) of the Artemis cult gave it prestige and economic power. The removal of the lampstand is not merely spiritual but represents the loss of the community\'s function within God\'s purpose.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Nicolaitans appear in the letters to Ephesus (2:6) and Pergamum (2:15), where their teaching is identified with the teaching of Balaam — accommodating to idol-food and sexual immorality (2:14). Patristic sources (Irenaeus, Clement of Alexandria) connect the Nicolaitans to Nicolas of Antioch (one of the seven deacons of Acts 6:5), though this identification is disputed. The group likely advocated a form of accommodation to Greco-Roman social practices — participating in trade guild banquets, eating food sacrificed to idols — under the rubric of Christian freedom from Jewish food laws.</p>',
    "7": '<p>\'The tree of life\' promised to the conqueror is drawn from Gen 2:9 and 3:22-24, where access to the tree was blocked after the fall. The tree of life in Jewish and early Christian tradition represented the eschatological reversal of the consequences of Adam\'s sin — access restored, mortality overcome. The \'Paradise of God\' (<em>paradeisos tou Theou</em>) is the LXX term for the Garden of Eden (Gen 2-3), now applied to the eschatological new creation. The Ephesian community, which lived in the shadow of the elaborate sacred garden precinct of Artemis\'s temple, is promised entrance into a greater and more enduring paradise.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Smyrna (modern Izmir) was one of the most beautiful cities of antiquity — it called itself \'first of Asia in beauty and size\' and was known for its elegant layout, its gold crown of hills, and its harbor. It was one of the most loyal cities to Rome in all of Asia: it had established a temple to Roma (the goddess of Rome) in 195 BCE, long before any other city, and had a temple to the Emperor Tiberius. The imperial cult was particularly strong here. The Jewish community in Smyrna had close relations with Roman authorities and was hostile to the Christian movement, informing on believers to magistrates.</p>',
    "9": '<p>\'I know your poverty, yet you are rich\' contrasts material and spiritual standing. Smyrna was a prosperous commercial city; the Christian community there was apparently economically marginalized — possibly because exclusion from the trade guilds (which required participation in pagan rites) cut them off from commercial networks. \'Those who say they are Jews and are not\' — the Jewish community in Smyrna had collaborated with Roman authorities against Christians; by rejecting Jesus as Messiah and opposing his followers, they had, from John\'s perspective, forfeited their identity as the covenant people of God.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The \'ten days\' of testing directly alludes to Daniel 1:12-15, where Daniel and his companions proposed a ten-day test of their diet before the Babylonian court. The ten-day period was therefore a recognized figure for a bounded, defined trial in Jewish tradition — not an indefinitely long persecution, but a specific duration with a specific end. The \'crown of life\' (<em>stephanos tēs zōēs</em>) uses the athletic victory-wreath image: Smyrna was famous for its athletic games (the Olympia) and the crowns awarded to victors. The imagery was locally resonant.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The \'second death\' from which the conqueror is exempt becomes explicit in Rev 20:6, 14 as the lake of fire — permanent separation from God after final judgment. The contrast with the \'first death\' (physical death) is significant for a community facing martyrdom: physical death is not the ultimate threat, but the second death is. For believers willing to die rather than deny Christ, this promise reframes the martyrdom choice: the death Rome threatens is not the worst possible outcome.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Pergamum (modern Bergama) was the former capital of the Roman province of Asia and remained one of the most important cities of the region, sitting on a dramatic acropolis. It was the location of the first imperial cult temple in Asia (built 29 BCE under Augustus), making it the symbolic center of emperor worship in the province. The proconsul of Asia, when he resided in Pergamum, exercised the <em>ius gladii</em> (right of the sword) — the power to execute criminals and political offenders. Christ\'s double-edged sword (v. 12) counters the proconsul\'s sword: the ultimate judicial authority belongs not to Rome but to Christ.</p>',
    "13": '<p>\'Satan\'s throne\' at Pergamum has been identified with several candidates: (1) the Great Altar of Zeus, a massive structure on the acropolis (now reconstructed in the Pergamon Museum, Berlin), one of the most impressive monuments of the Hellenistic world; (2) the imperial cult temple to Augustus; (3) the famous Asclepius healing sanctuary — the Asclepeion was one of the most important healing shrines in the ancient world (Galen was born in Pergamum), and its symbol was the serpent. Any or all of these could have made Pergamum feel like the seat of demonic power to first-century Christians. Antipas is named as the only individual martyr mentioned in the seven letters.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Balaam\'s teaching (Num 22-25, 31:8, 16) was the classic OT example of the corrupting teacher who led Israel into sexual immorality with Moabite women and idol worship at Baal-Peor (Num 25:1-9). The use of the Balaam story to describe the Nicolaitan-type teachers shows that the pattern was recognized: an outside religious teacher enabling accommodation to idolatrous practices for economic or social gain. The specific combination of idol-food and sexual immorality reflects the realities of Greco-Roman banqueting culture, where temple feasts routinely combined both elements.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Nicolaitans appear again here alongside the Balaam-teaching as a parallel or overlapping movement. The church at Pergamum tolerates these teachers (unlike Ephesus which rejected them), suggesting a community divided on the issue of accommodation to Roman social norms. The city\'s status as a center of the imperial cult created particular pressure: participating in civic religious life was effectively mandatory for anyone seeking advancement in Pergamum\'s social and commercial networks.</p>',
    "16": '<p>\'The sword of my mouth\' in v. 16 mirrors the proconsul\'s sword (v. 12) — the local Roman authority that could execute Christians. The warning that Christ will come and \'make war\' against the false teachers with his word reframes the power dynamic: the word of Christ is more powerful than the sword of Rome. This is not a prediction of military conflict but of the judicial power of divine proclamation to expose and condemn false teaching.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The \'hidden manna\' promised to the conqueror is the eschatological reversal of the idol-food issue. Jewish tradition held that Jeremiah hid the golden jar of manna (preserved from the wilderness period, Exod 16:32-34; Heb 9:4) before the Babylonian destruction, and that it would be revealed when the Messiah came (2 Macc 2:4-8; 2 Baruch 29:8). The heavenly manna is thus the alternative to the idol-food of the guild banquets. The \'white stone with a new name\' evokes two practices: the white stone as an acquittal token in Greek judicial proceedings (white = innocent, black = guilty) and the <em>tessera hospitalis</em> (hospitality token) that granted access to a private banquet — a permanent invitation to the eschatological feast.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Thyatira was the smallest of the seven cities but the most commercially active, located on a trade route between Pergamum and Sardis. It was a center of dyeing (purple and scarlet cloth), bronze-working, pottery, and other crafts. Lydia of Thyatira was a \'seller of purple cloth\' in Philippi (Acts 16:14), illustrating the city\'s commercial reach. More than any other of the seven cities, Thyatira was dominated by trade guilds — associations of craftsmen and merchants that combined economic function with regular religious banquets to patron deities. The letter\'s concern with idol-food and sexual immorality (v. 20) is directly connected to guild life.</p>',
    "19": '<p>\'Your recent deeds surpass your earlier ones\' — the Thyatiran community was growing in love, faith, service, and endurance. This positive trajectory makes the toleration of \'Jezebel\' more problematic, not less: a community capable of such love and service was not corrupt but was allowing a corrupting influence to operate unchecked. The irony is that the same virtues (love, service) that made the community flourishing also made it reluctant to exclude the influential teacher who claimed prophetic authority.</p>',
    "20": '<p>\'Jezebel\' is a symbolic name, not the person\'s actual name — it identifies the teacher with the historical Jezebel of 1 Kgs 16-21: the Phoenician queen who married Ahab and systematically introduced Baal worship into Israel, eliminated the prophets of YHWH, and protected the false prophet Balaam\'s equivalent (the 450 prophets of Baal, 1 Kgs 18:19). The self-styled prophetess at Thyatira was doing the same thing in miniature: replacing YHWH-worship with accommodation to idolatry. The specific issue — eating food sacrificed to idols — was directly relevant to the guild-participation question that Thyatira\'s commercial culture made unavoidable.</p>',
    "21": '<p>\'I gave her time to repent, and she is not willing to repent.\' The extended opportunity for repentance before judgment is a consistent pattern in OT prophetic preaching (Jer 7:13, 25; 25:3; 35:15; Ezek 3:19) and in Jesus\'s ministry (Luke 13:6-9, the parable of the fig tree given one more year). The specificity \'I gave her time\' implies a prior visitation or warning — the false prophet at Thyatira has not been operating without challenge but has refused to change despite divine patience.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The threat to \'throw her onto a bed of suffering\' (v. 22) uses the bed as both the location of the sin and the instrument of punishment — a rhetorical inversion common in prophetic judgment oracles (Amos 6:4-7: those who reclined on beds of ivory will be the first to go into exile; Isa 28:20: the bed is too short to stretch out on). \'Those who commit adultery with her\' encompasses both literal sexual immorality at temple banquets and the metaphorical adultery of spiritual unfaithfulness — the two registers operate simultaneously throughout Revelation.</p>',
    "23": '<p>\'I am the one who searches minds and hearts\' is drawn from the OT divine-judge formula: Jer 17:10 (\'I the LORD search the heart and test the mind\'); Ps 7:9 (\'God who tests minds and hearts\'). The \'kidneys\' (rendered \'minds\' in most translations) were in Semitic physiology the seat of conscience and deep motivation — to search the kidneys is to examine what cannot be hidden. This claim to comprehensive moral knowledge of all the churches is what makes the judgment credible: there are no hidden accommodations that Christ has not seen.</p>',
    "24": '<p>\'The deep things of Satan\' — the false prophetess\'s followers apparently used the language of \'depth\' or \'deep things\' (<em>ta bathē</em>) to describe their teaching, possibly claiming access to spiritual depth through transgressive behavior. This gnosticizing claim — that the spiritually mature can participate in idol-feasts without defilement because they \'know\' that idols are nothing — resonates with the libertarian argument Paul addresses in 1 Cor 8-10. The response both there and here is that the question is not about spiritual status but about the damage done to others and the allegiance declared.</p>',
    "25": '<p>\'Hold on to what you have until I come.\' The parousia as the termination point of the requirement to endure is a consistent eschatological structure in the NT epistles (1 Cor 4:5; 1 Thess 4:15-17; 2 Tim 4:8). The faithfulness required is not permanent self-sustaining virtue but endurance until the arrival of the one who is coming. The eschatological horizon makes the present demands finite: \'hold until I come\' implies the coming is real and the waiting has an end.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The promise of \'authority over the nations\' draws on Ps 2:8-9, where the messianic king receives the nations as his inheritance and rules them with an iron rod. The sharing of this authority with \'the one who overcomes\' participates in the consistent Revelation theme that the community shares in Christ\'s victory and rule (3:21; 5:10; 20:4, 6). In the context of a community subject to Roman provincial authority, the eschatological reversal is striking: those who now have no authority over nations will then exercise it.</p>',
    "27": '<p>\'He will rule them with an iron rod and shatter them like clay vessels\' quotes Ps 2:9 — but in the LXX, the verb for \'rule\' is <em>poimainō</em> (to shepherd), which has a range from pastoral care to strict oversight. The iron-rod shepherding is a paradox that Revelation sustains throughout: the Lamb who was slain is also the shepherd with an iron rod; the same Christ who feeds and leads (7:17) also rules with uncompromising authority. The promise to the conqueror extends this paradoxical lordship to the faithful community.</p>',
    "28": '<p>\'The morning star\' is identified as Christ himself in 22:16 (\'I am the bright morning star\'). The background includes Num 24:17 (\'a star shall come out of Jacob\'), the messianic star prophecy that was interpreted by multiple Second Temple groups (the Dead Sea Scrolls, rabbinic tradition, and the early church) as referring to the coming Messiah. The promise to give the overcomer \'the morning star\' is thus a promise to give Christ himself — the fullest possible eschatological gift, the presence of the Messiah as the final dawn.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The formula \'Let anyone who has an ear hear what the Spirit says to the churches\' closes each of the seven letters, creating a liturgical refrain. Its movement from the singular \'to you\' (the specific community addressed) to the plural \'to the churches\' ensures that no letter is merely parochial — what is spoken to one is meant for all seven, and through them for all communities at any time. The same formula appears in Jesus\'s parables (Matt 11:15; 13:9, 43), connecting the Spirit\'s speech through Revelation to Jesus\'s own teaching practice.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p>Sardis (modern Sart) was the ancient capital of Lydia under King Croesus (560–547 BCE), proverbially the wealthiest ruler in the ancient world (\'rich as Croesus\' was a common expression). The city was twice captured by surprise attack despite its apparently impregnable acropolis: Cyrus the Great took Sardis in 547 BCE when a Persian soldier climbed the cliff that the defenders considered unscalable; Antiochus III repeated the feat in 214 BCE by the same route. Both times, the defenders\' overconfidence — their reputation for security — was the fatal vulnerability. Christ\'s warning \'I will come like a thief\' (v. 3) speaks with particular local resonance to a city whose twice-repeated disaster had been caused by exactly this failure.</p>',
    "2": '<p>\'Strengthen what remains and is about to die\' — the image is of a dying ember or a community whose initial energy has not been sustained. The Sardis church had a reputation (\'a name\') for being alive but was spiritually inert. This gap between reputation and reality was a recognized danger in both Jewish wisdom literature and early Christian teaching: Matt 23\'s \'whitewashed tombs\' make the same point. The works found \'incomplete\' (<em>peplērōmena</em>) suggests a pattern of starting but not finishing — enthusiasm that does not sustain through to completion.</p>',
    "3": '<p>\'I will come like a thief, and you will not know at what hour I will come against you\' — the thief-coming metaphor for divine judgment appears in early Christian tradition (Matt 24:43; 1 Thess 5:2; 2 Pet 3:10) as a figure for unprepared encounter with divine judgment. Applied here to the Sardis church, it specifically reverses the proud security of the city that was twice taken by surprise: the community that has settled into false security will be surprised by Christ\'s judgment as surely as the city was surprised by its enemies.</p>',
    "4": '<p>\'A few people in Sardis who have not soiled their garments\' — the garment metaphor for moral and spiritual purity runs throughout OT and early Jewish literature. Soiled garments represent defilement; clean/white garments represent righteousness and covenant faithfulness (Zech 3:3-5, where Joshua the high priest has filthy garments replaced with clean ones). The commercial wealth of Sardis included a significant textile trade: the city was known for its fine wool and purple dyeing. The metaphor of clean clothing had particular resonance in a textile city where the quality of one\'s garments marked social status.</p>',
    "5": '<p>\'I will never blot his name out of the book of life\' — the book of life is a concept rooted in Moses\'s intercession (Exod 32:32-33: \'blot me out of your book\'), the Psalms (Ps 69:28), and Daniel (Dan 12:1: \'everyone whose name is found written in the book shall be delivered\'). In the Roman world, each city maintained a civic register (<em>album</em>) listing its citizens; when a citizen died, their name was erased. The eschatological book of life is the divine counterpart: names written there are not subject to erasure by death or any other power.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Standard closing formula; see notes on 2:7. The repetition creates a liturgical rhythm across all seven letters — the Spirit\'s address to one community is for all.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Philadelphia (modern Alashehir) was founded ca. 159–138 BCE by the Pergamene king Attalus II Philadelphus (hence its name: \'brotherly love city\') to serve as a center for spreading Greek language and culture in the Lydian hinterland. The city sat on a major route into the interior plateau of Asia — its position as a gateway city gave it commercial and strategic significance. Philadelphia suffered devastatingly from the great earthquake of 17 CE (the same quake that destroyed Sardis): the city was so badly shaken by aftershocks that many residents lived in tents outside the city walls for years. The city was rebuilt with significant help from Emperor Tiberius, who remitted taxes for a period. The key imagery of v. 7-8 (open door, pillar in the temple) would have been vivid to earthquake survivors.</p>',
    "8": '<p>\'I have placed before you an open door that no one is able to shut.\' The city of Philadelphia served as the gateway to the Phrygian plateau — its location made it a center for trade routes connecting the Aegean coast with the interior. The \'open door\' for the Philadelphia church may reflect both missionary opportunity (the city\'s historic role as a cultural gateway) and community access — despite \'little power\' (social and economic marginality), the community had received an open door that the opposition (the \'synagogue of Satan,\' v. 9) could not close.</p>',
    "9": '<p>\'Those of the synagogue of Satan who say they are Jews and are not\' — as in Smyrna (2:9), the local Jewish community\'s opposition to the Christian movement is addressed. Philadelphia had a significant Jewish community, and the dispute over who constitutes the \'true Israel\' — a question running through Paul\'s letters (Rom 2:28-29; 9:6; Phil 3:3; Gal 6:16) — was live and local. The promise that these opponents \'will come and bow down before your feet\' inverts the Isaiah promises where nations bow before restored Israel (Isa 45:14; 49:23; 60:14) — the eschatological vindication of the church.</p>',
    "10": '<p>\'I will keep you from the hour of trial that is coming on the whole world\' — the preposition <em>ek</em> (from out of) in \'keep you from\' has been debated for centuries as to whether it means preservation through or removal before the coming trial period. Both readings are exegetically possible. The key contextual point is the promise\'s ground: \'because you have kept my word about patient endurance\' — the keeping of the community is tied to the community\'s keeping of the word. Faithfulness is met with faithful protection.</p>',
    "11": '<p>\'Hold fast to what you have, so that no one may seize your crown\' — the victor\'s crown (<em>stephanos</em>) could be lost if one did not finish the race; the athletic image implies ongoing effort, not a past achievement that can be banked. In Philadelphia, the Neocaesarean games (instituted after the earthquake, honoring Tiberius) would have made the crown imagery locally familiar. The eschatological crown is contingent on perseverance: Christ is coming, and the question is whether one will still be holding what one received when he arrives.</p>',
    "12": '<p>\'I will make him a pillar in the temple of my God\' — after the 17 CE earthquake, pillars that survived when buildings collapsed became visible symbols of stability in the region. Travelers approaching Philadelphia often saw isolated pillars standing where their buildings had fallen. The eschatological promise to the Philadelphia community — \'you will be an immovable pillar in God\'s temple\' — would have resonated deeply with earthquake survivors who knew exactly what it meant for a pillar to outlast destruction. \'He will never go out of it again\' reverses the experience of those who had to leave the city during the aftershocks.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Standard closing formula; see notes on 2:7.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Laodicea (near modern Denizli) was the richest city of the seven churches\' region — a major banking center, the headquarters of the Ciceronian judicial circuit, and a prosperous commercial city. When the great earthquake of 60 CE struck (more devastating than the 17 CE quake that hit Philadelphia and Sardis), Laodicea refused the imperial aid offered by Rome and rebuilt entirely from its own resources — a demonstration of civic self-sufficiency and wealth that the city was proud of. This pride in not needing outside help directly parallels the church\'s attitude: \'I am rich, I have prospered, and I need nothing\' (v. 17). The community had absorbed the civic culture\'s self-confidence.</p>',
    "15": '<p>\'You are neither cold nor hot\' — Laodicea\'s water supply came via a six-mile aqueduct from hot springs at Hierapolis. By the time the water arrived at Laodicea, it was tepid — neither the refreshing cold water of Colossae\'s mountain springs nor the therapeutic hot water of Hierapolis\'s healing baths. Ancient visitors to Laodicea complained that the water was unpleasant due to its lukewarm temperature and mineral content. The imagery would have been immediately recognizable to any Laodicean: their city\'s notorious water problem became the vehicle for describing their spiritual condition.</p>',
    "16": '<p>\'I will spit you out of my mouth\' (<em>emesai</em>) — the visceral reaction of a body encountering something nauseating. The severity of the language directed at the wealthiest of the seven churches is deliberate: the community whose material comfort had insulated it from the urgency that marks the other six letters receives the harshest physical metaphor. The word \'about to\' (<em>mellō</em>) maintains the conditional structure — the vomiting is threatened, not yet enacted, leaving room for the repentance called for in v. 19.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Laodicea was known for three industries that become ironic commentary on the church\'s condition: (1) banking and financial wealth — the church says it is rich but is spiritually poor; (2) the black wool textile trade — Laodicean black sheep produced famous wool cloth, but the church needs white garments; (3) the Phrygian powder (<em>Phrygian collyrium</em>), a well-known eye salve produced and exported from the region — but the church needs \'eye salve\' of genuine spiritual vision. All three local products become the instruments of the rebuke.</p>',
    "18": '<p>\'Buy from me gold refined by fire\' — the commercial metaphor uses Laodicea\'s own marketplace language against it. The city\'s banking center (where people bought and sold) becomes the venue for a transaction with Christ: the currency is not wealth but suffering-tested faithfulness. The eye-salve remedy specifically plays on Laodicea\'s pharmaceutical reputation — the Asclepius temple at the nearby hot springs was a healing center, and the region\'s <em>collyrium</em> was exported widely. Christ offers what the region\'s pharmacy cannot: genuine healing of the deepest blindness.</p>',
    "19": '<p>\'Those whom I love, I rebuke and discipline.\' The father-child disciplinary relationship is drawn from Prov 3:11-12 (\'do not despise the LORD\'s discipline... for the LORD disciplines those he loves, as a father the son he delights in\') and Heb 12:5-11. The severity of the Laodicea letter is thus reframed as love\'s most direct intervention: not the absence of care but the most urgent form of it. \'Be zealous and repent\' — <em>zēleue</em> (aorist imperative, an immediate decisive burning of passion) is the specific antidote to lukewarmness: not moderation toward warmth but ignition.</p>',
    "20": '<p>\'Behold, I stand at the door and knock.\' The image of a host or friend standing outside a door and calling for entry reverses the normal social logic — in Greco-Roman hospitality culture, the householder received guests; here Christ stands outside waiting to be received by the community that should be hosting him. The shared meal (<em>deipnon</em>) promised is the main evening meal — in antiquity the most intimate and significant social bond, expressing covenant relationship and personal friendship. The promise is made to individuals within the church (\'if anyone hears\' — singular), indicating that even in a community where the corporate situation is dire, individual response remains possible.</p>',
    "21": '<p>\'To the one who overcomes, I will grant him to sit with me on my throne, as I also overcame and sat down with my Father on his throne.\' The highest promise of the seven letters is given to the community that appears least deserving of it — Laodicea, the lukewarm and self-satisfied church. The promise of sharing Christ\'s throne grounds the eschatological vision in Ps 110:1 (\'the LORD says to my Lord, sit at my right hand\') applied to Christ (Heb 1:3, 13; 8:1; 10:12). The community\'s participation in Christ\'s victory is presented as completed fact: as Christ \'overcame and sat down,\' so the overcomer will.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Standard closing formula; see notes on 2:7. The closing of the last letter with the same formula as the first six reinforces the circular, liturgical character of the seven letters as a unified whole addressed to the whole church.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "2": '<p>The \'throne in heaven\' is the central image of chs. 4–5 and the organizing axis of the entire book. In Jewish apocalyptic, the heavenly throne was the locus of divine sovereignty and the source from which all earthly history was governed. The <em>merkabah</em> tradition (throne-chariot mysticism, based primarily on Ezek 1 and Isa 6) was one of the most important streams of Jewish spirituality in the Second Temple period. The Mishnah (b. Hagigah 11b-16a) restricted who could study the chariot chapter of Ezekiel — its vision of the divine throne was considered too powerful and potentially dangerous for uninstructed study. John\'s vision opens this restricted domain to every member of the seven churches.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The description of the one on the throne through precious stones — jasper (translucent crystal, 21:11), carnelian (deep red), and emerald (green) — reflects the OT prohibition of any direct description of the divine form. Ezekiel also describes the enthroned figure through comparisons and colors rather than direct description (Ezek 1:26-28). The rainbow around the throne invokes the Noahic covenant sign (Gen 9:13-16): God\'s pledge of covenant faithfulness encircles his throne of judgment, reminding the seer that even divine wrath operates within the frame of covenant grace.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The twenty-four elders have been identified with several biblical or traditional groups: (1) the twenty-four priestly courses established by David for temple service (1 Chr 24:1-19) — the complete priestly rotation, representing all of Israel\'s worship; (2) the twelve patriarchs of Israel plus the twelve apostles of Christ — the two covenant communities together; (3) a council of angelic beings serving in the heavenly throne-room. Their white garments and victor\'s crowns (<em>stephanoi</em>, not royal <em>diadēmata</em>) favor a redeemed-community reading. Their seated position on thrones signals delegated authority — they rule because the one on the central throne has granted them rule.</p>',
    "5": '<p>\'From the throne came flashes of lightning, and rumblings and peals of thunder\' — the theophany formula of Exod 19:16-19 (lightning, thunder, thick cloud, loud trumpet at Sinai) recurs at each of Revelation\'s major structural turning points (8:5; 11:19; 16:18). The association of divine speech with thunder was well-established in OT and ancient Near Eastern tradition: Ps 29 describes YHWH\'s voice as thunder over the waters, the Sinai covenant was given in thunder, and the oracle at Delphi was preceded by loud sounds. The seven torches identified as the seven Spirits of God connect the Holy Spirit\'s full presence with the blazing light of God\'s holiness.</p>',
    "6": '<p>\'Before the throne was something like a sea of glass, like crystal.\' The crystalline sea in the heavenly temple corresponds to two OT images: the sapphire pavement under God\'s feet at Sinai (Exod 24:10, where the elders of Israel saw the God of Israel on what looked like a pavement of lapis lazuli) and the bronze sea (<em>yam</em>) in Solomon\'s temple (1 Kgs 7:23-26), the large basin in the temple courtyard used for priestly purification. The heavenly sea is the pure, glassy archetype of which the earthly temple basin was a shadow.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The four living creatures — lion, ox (or calf), human, eagle — combine Ezekiel\'s four-faced cherubim (Ezek 1:5-14, which have four faces: human, lion, ox, eagle) with Isaiah\'s seraphim (Isa 6:2-3, six-winged, crying \'holy, holy, holy\'). The tradition of linking the four Gospels with the four faces (lion = Matthew/Mark, ox = Luke, eagle = John, or similar assignments) begins with Irenaeus (ca. 180 CE, <em>Against Heresies</em> 3.11.8). The four creatures represent the fullness of living creation before the throne — wild (lion), domestic (ox), rational (human), and aerial (eagle) — all creation in ceaseless worship.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The Trisagion — \'Holy, holy, holy\' (<em>qadosh, qadosh, qadosh</em> in the Hebrew of Isa 6:3) — was already a central element of Jewish temple and synagogue worship. The Kedushah prayer in the Jewish liturgy, which continues to the present day, is built around this threefold acclamation of divine holiness from Isa 6:3. Early Christian worship adopted the Trisagion; it remains in the liturgies of Eastern and Western churches. The \'who was and is and is to come\' formula is the temporal expansion of the divine name of Exod 3:14 (\'I AM WHO I AM\') — divine existence without beginning or end.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The temporal conjunction \'whenever\' (<em>hotan</em>) + present-tense verbs describes an ongoing, continuous cycle of heavenly worship — not a single event but the unceasing liturgy of the throne-room. In Jewish understanding, the heavenly worship preceded and grounded earthly worship: the angels worshiped in heaven, and human worship on earth participated in and reflected the celestial liturgy. The elaborate temple liturgy of the Jerusalem temple (with its daily sacrifices, weekly Sabbath, and annual festivals) was understood as the earthly counterpart of a heavenly original.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The twenty-four elders casting their crowns before the throne enacts the ancient vassal-treaty practice: a subordinate king would remove his own crown before a superior sovereign to acknowledge their lordship. The suzerain-vassal treaties of the ancient Near East (well attested in Hittite and Assyrian documents) required the vassal to pay tribute and acknowledge the suzerain\'s absolute sovereignty. The heavenly throne-room enacts this protocol: every authority in creation acknowledges its derivative status before the one on the throne. The victor\'s crowns (<em>stephanoi</em>) they cast were given to them; they return what was always his.</p>',
    "11": '<p>\'Worthy are you, our Lord and God, to receive glory and honor and power\' — \'our Lord and God\' (<em>ho Kyrios kai ho Theos hēmōn</em>) is precisely the title that the Emperor Domitian demanded: according to Suetonius and Dio Cassius, Domitian insisted on being addressed as <em>Dominus et Deus noster</em> (our Lord and God). The heavenly doxology directly counters the imperial claim: the only Lord and God worthy of glory, honor, and power is the Creator, not the Caesar. For communities in the seven cities — where the imperial cult was practiced, where statues and temples honored the divine emperor — this doxology was a subversive act of allegiance.</p>'
  },
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>A scroll written \'on the inside and on the back\' (<em>esōthen kai opisthen</em>) is an <em>opisthographon</em> — a scroll with text on both sides of the papyrus or parchment. This was unusual and expensive; such scrolls signaled content of extraordinary fullness. The seven seals invoke Roman legal practice: a Roman will (<em>testamentum</em>) was sealed with seven seals by seven witnesses; to break the seals and open a will required proper authority. The sealed scroll in God\'s hand is thus the divine testament — the covenant will of God for history — which can only be opened by the one who is the proper heir and executor.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The \'mighty angel\' proclaiming \'who is worthy\' enacts a cosmic herald\'s announcement — the Roman practice of the <em>praeco</em> (herald) who announced public proclamations and court proceedings. The herald\'s question frames the scroll-opening as a worthiness contest: the issue is not power (God on the throne has all power) but moral and legal qualification. The contrast with Roman imperial propaganda is pointed: the emperor claimed <em>dignitas</em> (worthiness/dignity) to rule the world, but the actual scroll of history requires a different qualification — not conquest but sacrifice.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The exhaustive three-domain search (heaven, earth, under the earth) mirrors the cosmic legal proceedings of the OT (Deut 32:40; Isa 44:23; Phil 2:10) — the witness of the entire cosmos is gathered, and none qualifies. The Stoic philosophers of the Roman era believed in a rational principle (<em>logos</em>) that governed all of history; the Jewish apocalyptic tradition believed that God\'s hidden plan (<em>razim</em>, mysteries) controlled earthly events. Neither the Stoic world-reason nor the Jewish heavenly calendar can be opened by any creature.</p>',
    "4": '<p>John\'s weeping at the apparent absence of a worthy opener is not a loss of faith but a correct reading of the stakes: if no one can open the scroll, the martyrs\' prayers for vindication (6:9-10) will go unanswered, the suffering of the communities has no redemptive resolution, and history has no eschatological goal. The weeping is the appropriate response to a cosmos without hope — and sets up the resolution with maximum dramatic force.</p>',
    "5": '<p>\'The Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David\' — both titles are drawn from OT messianic expectation. Gen 49:9-10 (\'Judah is a lion\'s cub... the scepter shall not depart from Judah until Shiloh comes\') established the Judah-lion-scepter complex as a messianic expectation. Isa 11:1, 10 (\'a shoot from the stump of Jesse... the root of Jesse\') established the Davidic-root figure. By the Second Temple period, both texts were applied to the coming Messiah — John\'s audience would have recognized both titles immediately as pointing to the expected deliverer from David\'s line.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Lamb standing \'as though slain\' is the most concentrated Christological image in the NT. The \'Lamb\' image draws on multiple OT registers simultaneously: the Passover lamb (Exod 12:3-13) whose blood protected from the destroying angel; the daily temple burnt-offering of a year-old lamb (Exod 29:38-46); the suffering servant \'led like a lamb to the slaughter\' (Isa 53:7). The community that received Revelation was familiar with the Passover lamb (as Jewish Christians) and with the \'Lamb of God\' language from early Christian confession (John 1:29; 1 Pet 1:19; 1 Cor 5:7). The \'standing as though slain\' is the resurrection: slain but alive, wounded but standing.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Lamb approaching the throne and taking the scroll from God\'s right hand is an act of cosmic legal standing — only the heir can take the inheritance document. In the Roman law of succession, the <em>heres</em> (heir) was the person who had the legal right and capacity to receive and execute a will. The Lamb\'s taking of the scroll is the moment of his investiture as cosmic heir and executor of the divine will for history. The entire drama of chs. 6-22 unfolds as the Lamb executes what was sealed in the scroll.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Golden bowls full of incense identified as \'the prayers of the saints\' — this identification reveals the structure of the heavenly temple. The prayers of the communities in the seven cities, offered in their house-church gatherings on the Lord\'s Day, are present in the heavenly temple as incense before the throne. The incense altar (Exod 30:1-10) stood before the Holy of Holies — the prayers of God\'s people are not lost in the noise of the world but are received and held at the center of cosmic reality. The harps connect the scene to Levitical temple worship (1 Chr 25:1-8).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The \'new song\' (<em>ōdē kainē</em>) is a formula drawn from the Psalms (Ps 33:3; 40:3; 96:1; 98:1; 144:9; 149:1) and Isa 42:10, used to announce a new redemptive act of God requiring new praise. The formula signals not mere repetition of old hymns but improvised praise for an unprecedented event. The basis of the new song is the cross (\'you were slain\') and the resulting purchase (\'you ransomed people for God\') — the language of <em>agorazō</em> (to buy in the marketplace, specifically the slave market) frames the atonement as liberation from bondage at the price of the Lamb\'s blood.</p>',
    "10": '<p>\'You have made them a kingdom and priests to our God\' — the Exod 19:6 citation (\'a kingdom of priests, a holy nation\') is repeated from 1:6, now placed in the mouth of the heavenly choir as established fact. The future \'they shall reign on the earth\' points to the eschatological dimension: what is constituted in the cross is not yet fully enacted in earthly experience. The communities of the seven letters, under Roman provincial rule with no political authority, are told that they are the priestly kingdom whose reign over the earth is coming.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The escalating rings of participants in the heavenly liturgy mirror the expanding concentric circles of the Jerusalem temple: the Holy of Holies (the throne), the Holy Place (the twenty-four elders and four creatures), the court of priests (the inner ring of angels), and the outer courts (the innumerable multitude). The angelic host of \'myriads of myriads and thousands of thousands\' quotes Dan 7:10 (the divine court before the Ancient of Days). The heavenly liturgy thus includes the full range of creaturely worshipers from the innermost divine precincts to the outermost edges of creation.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The sevenfold doxology to the Lamb — \'power, wealth, wisdom, might, honor, glory, and blessing\' — has a structural parallel in the Roman imperial acclamation: the emperor received tribute, honor, and glory at public ceremonies. The throne-room ceremony of Revelation 5 enacts a counter-imperial investiture: not the emperor but the Lamb who was slain receives the universe\'s tribute. The seven attributes (seven = completeness) represent the total of what all of creation owes to its true Lord.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The cosmic doxology \'to him who sits on the throne and to the Lamb\' from every creature in every domain of creation (heaven, earth, under the earth, sea) is the final answer to the imperial demand for universal worship. Roman imperial propaganda presented the emperor as the center of a universal order — coins, temples, and public art proclaimed his claim to universal dominion. The throne-room vision counters this with a vision of genuine universal worship: every creature freely offering to God and the Lamb what the emperor demanded and could never genuinely receive.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The double \'Amen\' from the four creatures and the prostration of the twenty-four elders closes the throne-room vision with liturgical completion. The \'Amen\' as the assembly\'s seal of a doxology was a feature of both Jewish synagogue and early Christian worship (1 Cor 14:16; Justin Martyr, <em>First Apology</em> 65: \'all the people present say Amen\' to the prayers). The entire vision of chs. 4–5 is framed by worship — it opens with the Trisagion (4:8) and closes with cosmic prostration — establishing that the ultimate response to the revelation of who God is and what the Lamb has done is worship.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation')
    merge_comm(existing, REVELATION)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation', existing)

    il = json.loads((ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / 'revelation.json').read_text())
    all_ok = True
    for ch in range(1, 6):
        ck = str(ch)
        il_vv = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys())
        out_vv = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = sorted(il_vv - out_vv, key=int)
        if missing:
            print(f'  ch{ch}: MISSING {missing}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'  ch{ch}: complete ({len(out_vv)} verses) ✓')
    if all_ok:
        print('  All chapters complete ✓')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
